/tvseriesfinale.com/tv-show/better-call-saul-season-three-ratings/ |title=Better Call Saul: Season Three Ratings |work=TV Series Finale |date=June 27, 2017 |accessdate=July 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n| link4             = Better Call Saul (season 4)\n| timeslot4         = Monday 9:00 pm\n| timeslot_length4  = 1\n| episodes4         = 10\n| start4            = August 6, 2018\n| startrating4      = 1.77<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/monday-cable-ratings-august-6-2018/ |title=Monday cable ratings: 'Better Call Saul' returns down, 'WWE Raw' slips |work=TV by the Numbers |first=Alex |last=Welch |date=August 7, 2018 |accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref>\n| end4              = October 8, 2018\n| endrating4        = 1.53<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/daily-ratings/monday-cable-ratings-oct-8-2018/ |title=Monday cable ratings: 'Better Call Saul' finale holds steady, 'Love & Hip Hop: Hollywood' dips |work=TV by the Numbers |first=Alex |last=Welch |date=October 9, 2018 |accessdate=October 9, 2018}}</ref>\n| viewers4          = 1.49<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvseriesfinale.com/tv-show/better-call-saul-season-four-ratings/ |title=Better Call Saul: Season Four Ratings |work=TV Series Finale |date=October 9, 2018 |accessdate=October 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n| link5             = Better Call Saul (season 5)\n| timeslot5         = Sunday 10:00 pm (premiere)<br />Monday 9:00 pm\n| timeslot_length5  = 1\n| episodes5         = 10\n| start5            = February 23, 2020\n| startrating5      = 1.60<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-sunday-cable-originals-network-finals-2-23-2020.html |title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Sunday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 2.23.2020 |last=Metcalf |first=Mitch |date=February 25, 2020 |work=Showbuzz Daily |accessdate=February 25, 2020}}</ref>\n| end5              = April 20, 2020\n| endrating5        = 1.59<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-monday-cable-originals-network-finals-4-20-2020.html |title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Monday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 4.20.2020 |last=Metcalf |first=Mitch |date=April 21, 2020 |work=Showbuzz Daily |accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n| viewers5          = 1.37<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tvseriesfinale.com/tv-show/better-call-saul-season-five-ratings/ |title=Better Call Saul: Season Five Ratings |work=TV Series Finale |date=April 21, 2020 |accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Home media ==\nThe first season was released on [[Blu-ray]] and DVD in [[DVD region code#Region codes and countries|region 1]] on November 10, 2015; bonus features include audio commentaries for every episode, uncensored episodes, deleted scenes, gag reel, and several behind-the-scenes featurettes. A limited edition Blu-ray set was also released with 3D packaging and a postcard vinyl of the ''Better Call Saul'' theme song by [[Junior Brown]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Better-Saul-Season-1-Press-Release/21558 |title=Better Call Saul \u2013 Sony's Official Press Release for 'Season 1' on DVD and Blu-ray |publisher=TVShowsOnDVD.com |first=David |last=Lambert |date=September 22, 2015 |accessdate=September 23, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923171953/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Better-Saul-Season-1-Press-Release/21558 |archivedate=September 23, 2015}}</ref> The second season was released on Blu-ray and DVD in region 1 on November 15, 2016; bonus features include audio commentaries for every episode and several behind-the-scenes featurettes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Better-Saul-Season-2/22667 |title=Better Call Saul \u2013 Blu-rays, DVDs for 'Season 2': Date, Cost, Packaging, Extras! |publisher=TVShowsOnDVD.com |first=David |last=Lambert |date=September 20, 2016 |accessdate=January 15, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116181910/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Better-Saul-Season-2/22667 |archivedate=January 16, 2017}}</ref> The third season was released on Blu-ray and DVD in region 1 on January 16, 2018; bonus features include audio commentaries for every episode and several behind-the-scenes featurettes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Better-Saul-Season-3/23831 |title=Better Call Saul \u2013 'Season 3' DVDs, Blu-rays: Street Date Confirmed, Front and Rear Package Art |publisher=TVShowsOnDVD.com |first=David |last=Lambert |date=November 27, 2017 |accessdate=January 16, 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117011913/http://www.tvshowsondvd.com/news/Better-Saul-Season-3/23831 |archivedate=January 17, 2018}}</ref> The fourth season was released on Blu-ray and DVD in region 1 on May 7, 2019; bonus features include audio commentary for every episode and several behind-the-scenes featurettes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=24774 |title=Better Call Saul: Season Four Blu-ray |publisher=Blu-ray.com |date=March 12, 2019 |accessdate=March 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\n===Web series===\nIn 2017, before the release of the third season of ''Better Call Saul,'' AMC published on their website a 10-episode web series called ''Los Pollos Hermanos Employee Training'', celebrating the return of Gus Fring. Following the success of the latter, which won the Emmy for Outstanding Short Form Comedy or Drama Series at the [[69th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]], AMC published another 10-episode web series called ''Madrigal Electromotive Security Training'' in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/emmys-revoke-2-nominations-for-better-call-saul-employee-training-web-series-due-to-running-time/ |title=Emmys Revoke 2 Nominations for 'Better Call Saul Employee Training' Web Series Due to Running Time |website=The Wrap |first=Reid |last=Nakamura |date=July 19, 2019 |accessdate=December 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Comics===\nAMC has released two [[digital comic]] books for ''Better Call Saul''. The first, titled ''Better Call Saul: Client Development'', released in February 2015, in advance of the series premiere, details the history of [[Saul Goodman|Saul]] and [[Mike Ehrmantraut|Mike]], acting as a spin-off of the ''[[Breaking Bad]]'' [[Better Call Saul (Breaking Bad)|episode]] that introduced Saul.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gonzalez |first=Sandra |title=AMC unveils 'Better Call Saul' digital comic book ahead of series premiere |publisher=Mashable |date=February 4, 2015 |url=http://mashable.com/2015/02/04/better-call-saul-comic-book/ |accessdate=May 9, 2016}}</ref> In February 2016, in advance of the second-season premiere, AMC released ''Better Call Saul: Saul Goodman and the Justice Consortium in the Clutches of the Judgernaut!''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://archive.nerdist.com/better-call-saul-has-its-own-digital-comic-book-with-flying-jimmy/ |title=BETTER CALL SAUL Has Its Own Digital Comic Book, With Flying Jimmy |publisher=Nerdist |first=Michael |last=Walsh |date=February 12, 2016 |accessdate=May 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q14925221|c=category:Better Call Saul |v=no|voy=Breaking Bad|n=no|s=no|wikt=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|b=no}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.amc.com/shows/better-call-saul|''Better Call Saul''}} \u2013 official site\n* {{IMDb title|3032476}}\n\n{{Better Call Saul|state=expanded}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for ''Better Call Saul''\n|list =\n{{Satellite Award Best Drama Television Series}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Action-Thriller Television Series}}\n{{TCA Award for Outstanding Achievement in Drama}}\n{{TCA Award for Outstanding New Program}}\n{{WritersGuildofAmericaEpisodicDramaScreenplay}}\n}}\n{{Breaking Bad}}\n{{AMC Shows}}\n\n[[Category:Better Call Saul| ]]\n[[Category:2015 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s American legal television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American crime drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American black comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American legal television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American crime drama television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American black comedy television series]]\n[[Category:AMC (TV channel) original programming]]\n[[Category:American prequel television series]]\n[[Category:Breaking Bad]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Nonlinear narrative television series]]\n[[Category:Saturn Award-winning television series]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Vince Gilligan]]\n[[Category:Television series by Sony Pictures Television]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 2000s]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Works about Mexican drug cartels]]\n", "name_user": "Drovethrughosts", "label": "safe", "comment": "Harmonize whitespace in citation templates (usinga script)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Better_Call_Saul"}
{"title_page": "Clare Grogan", "text_new": "{{about|the actress and singer|the camogie player|Claire Grogan}}\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2009}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n<!--PLEASE NOTE:  the references in this article are in a list format, which means the data for the refs is in the References section, not in the body of the article.  If you add a new ref, please follow this format.  If you delete some text that includes a ref, please preview the whole page and check that you haven't created a ref error in the References section.\n-->\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name       = Clare Grogan\n| image      = Clare Grogan.jpg\n| caption    = Grogan performing with Altered Images\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1962|03|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| other_names =\n| genre       = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[rock music|rock]], [[New wave music|new wave]]\n| occupation = Singer, actress\n| background = solo_singer <!-- includes lead singers of bands -->\n| associated_acts = [[Altered Images]]\n}}\n'''Claire Patricia Grogan''' (born 17 March 1962), known professionally as '''Clare Grogan''' or sometimes as '''C. P. Grogan''', is a Scottish actress and singer. She is best known as the lead singer of the 1980s [[new wave music]] group [[Altered Images]] and for supporting roles in the 1981 film ''[[Gregory's Girl]]'' and the science fiction sitcom ''[[Red Dwarf]]'' as the first incarnation of [[Kristine Kochanski]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dave.uktv.co.uk/red-dwarf/red-dwarf-cast/article/clare-grogan-profile/|accessdate=9 February 2020|title=Clare Grogan}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Glasgow]], Grogan and her two sisters all attended the [[Notre Dame High School (Glasgow)|Notre Dame Convent School]].<ref name=stv/>\n\nAged 17 while dancing at the Glasgow College of Technology, a fight broke out nearby between several patrons. Grogan attempted to head away from the violence but was injured by thrown broken glass, causing a deep facial wound and prominent scar on the left side of her face. Grogan states that her parents still find it hard to read about the incident. She began filming ''Gregory's Girl'' just three months after the incident.<ref name=\"Metro Ian Beale\"/> In 1998, while she was working in Theatre at Watford, it was discovered part of the glass was still in the facial tissue and had to be surgically removed. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/uk/the-herald-1130/20111114/282106338437237|title=Centre Stage:Clare Gorgan on Success|website=www.pressreader.com|publisher=The Herald|date=2011-11-14}}</ref>\n\n==Acting career==\nOriginally a member of Scottish Youth Theatre, she was originally obliged to appear as 'C.P. Grogan' because there was already a member of [[Equity (trade union)|Equity]] named Claire Grogan (the other Claire Grogan went on to become a photographer). She would later drop the ''i'' from her first name.<ref name=standard/>\n\nWhile working as a [[waitress]] at the Spaghetti Factory [[restaurant]] in Glasgow, she was spotted by film director [[Bill Forsyth]].<ref name=herald/> This led to her breakthrough acting role in 1981's ''[[Gregory's Girl]]'' as Susan. Because of her facial wound there were objections from the producers, but Forsyth refused to recast the role and Grogan was filmed mostly in profile. When filmed in close up, makeup artists covered Grogan's scar with Derma wax.<ref name=stv2/>{{dead link|date=May 2014}}\n\nIn 1984, she played Charlotte in Forsyth's ''[[Comfort and Joy (1984 film)|Comfort and Joy]]''. In 1985, she was the receptionist in the [[BBC Television]] version of ''[[Blott on the Landscape]]''. She had a recurring role playing [[Red Dwarf characters#David Lister|Dave Lister]]'s would-be [[love-interest]], [[Kristine Kochanski]], in series 1, 2 and 6 of the TV show ''[[Red Dwarf]]''. However she was deemed too old for the role by Series 7 - despite being younger than most of her male counterparts - and replaced by [[Chlo\u00eb Annett]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/12803442.how-clare-survived-25-years-in-showbiz/|title=How Clare survived 25 years in showbiz|website=Evening Times}}</ref>. Grogan has also appeared in ''[[Father Ted]]'' (episode \"[[Rock-a-Hula Ted]]\") as a feminist rock singer and in ''[[EastEnders]]'' as [[Ian Beale]]'s love interest, [[Ros Thorne]] (1997\u20131998).\n\nGrogan played the part of Rita in a stage adaptation of ''[[Educating Rita]]'' at Dundee Repertory Theatre in 1987.<ref name=sta/>\n\nIn 1996 she played a fitness instructor on the [[Edinburgh Fringe]] in the play ''[[Lady Macbeth Firmed My Buttocks]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/fringe-round-up-lady-macbeth-firmed-my-buttocks-1309779.html|title=fringe round-up: Lady Macbeth Firmed My Buttocks|date=15 August 1996|website=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nShe had the role of Maggie in a 1998 comedy ''Jilting Joe'', played an Eye-Surgeon in a 2002 short film ''Bury It'', appeared in ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'' in 2003, and performed another [[Edinburgh Fringe]] play ''Forbidden'' in 2004, as Lily, married to a WW2 Nazi officer but falling in love with a young Jewish woman. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edinburghguide.com/news/theatre/8289-claregrogantopresentcriticsawardfortheatreinscotland|title=Clare Grogan to Present Critics' Award for Theatre in Scotland - Edinburgh Guide|website=www.edinburghguide.com}}</ref> \n\nIn 2006 Grogan portrayed Sandra Reeves, a control-freak office manager, in a film ''The Penalty King'' <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theargus.co.uk/news/5103049.altered-images-star-films-in-brighton/|title=Altered Images star films in Brighton|website=The Argus}}</ref> played Cathy in an episode of ''[[Sea of Souls]]'', and May, Danny's mother, in the Scottish sit-com ''[[Legit (2006 TV series)|Legit]]''. She appeared in the video for [[Peter Kay]] and [[Matt Lucas]]' charity single \"[[I'm Gonna Be (500 Miles)#Comic Relief|I'm Gonna Be (500 Miles)]]\", recorded for [[Comic Relief (charity)|Comic Relief]]'s Red Nose Day 2007, along with two TV films ''Wedding Belles'' and ''Forgiven''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0342931/|title=Clare Grogan|website=IMDb}}</ref>\n\nGrogan had a role in the 2011 TV series ''[[Skins (TV series)|Skins]]'' as Shelley, mother of [[Mini McGuinness]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/a302415/clare-grogan-explains-skins-role/|title=Clare Grogan explains 'Skins' role|first=Catriona|last=Wightman|date=7 February 2011|website=Digital Spy}}</ref> and played Jenny Ferris in the Scottish gangster film ''[[The Wee Man]]'' in 2013. \nShe starred as Myriam in the 2017 film ''Delirium'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news-2-15012/interview-clare-grogan-1-4535598|title=Interview: Clare Grogan|website=www.scotsman.com}}</ref> filmed entirely at [[Royal Holloway, University of London]].\n\n==Music career==\nGrogan developed her singing career as the lead singer of [[Altered Images]], originally a five-piece band that included [[Johnny McElhone]] (later of the Scottish [[rock band]] [[Texas (band)|Texas]]), whom she met while studying for her [[Higher (Scottish)|Highers]]. It became a four-person band with the departure of two members and the addition of Stephen Lironi, who played both [[guitar]] and [[drum kit|drums]]. The band had a string of hits in the early 1980s, including \"[[Happy Birthday (Altered Images song)|Happy Birthday]]\", \"[[Don't Talk to Me About Love]]\", \"[[I Could Be Happy]]\" and \"See Those Eyes\". The group split up after the release of their third album, ''[[Bite (Altered Images album)|Bite]]'' (1983).\n\nIn 1984, Grogan made a cameo appearance in the music video to \"[[Young at Heart (Bananarama song)|Young at Heart]]\" by [[The Bluebells]].\n\nGrogan later attempted a [[solo (music)|solo]] career, but after her [[single (music)|single]] \"Love Bomb\" failed to gain chart success in 1987, her album ''Trash Mad'' was never released. Grogan formed Universal Love School in 1989 with Lironi, performing a series of gigs around the UK. However, it was short-lived and produced no hit singles. In 2000, she contributed vocals to the song \"Night Falls Like a Grand Piano\" on [[The 6ths]]' album ''[[Hyacinths and Thistles]]''. She recorded a version of \"Angels with Dirty Faces\" for the [[Frankie Miller]] tribute album. The track \"Her Hooped Dream\" appears on ''The Ultimate Celtic Album''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Ultimate-Celtic-Album-Various-artists/dp/B005FY0E5M|accessdate=9 February 2020|title=The Ultimate Celtic Album}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Grogan performed as 'Altered Images' on the [[Here and Now Tour]] which featured other well known artists from the 1980s. She performed on similar tours in 2005, 2008 and 2009. She appeared with [[Chesney Hawkes]], [[Toyah Willcox]] and [[Limahl]] as 'The 80s Supergroup' in the 2011 series of ''[[Let's Dance for Comic Relief]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/1NWMGqXS1Rwy5Svp726DqK1/contestants-the-final|accessdate=9 February 2020|title=Contestants - The Final}}</ref>\n\nGrogan sometimes covers for radio presenters on [[BBC 6 Music]], most often for [[Nemone]] and sometimes [[Liz Kershaw]].{{cn|date=December 2018}}\n\nGrogan appeared in Series 2, Episode 2 of [[John Shuttleworth (character)|John Shuttleworth's]] Lounge Music on [[BBC Radio 4]] on 27 November 2016.<ref name = \"John Shuttleworth\" />\n\nClare Grogan is the inspiration for the song \"[[True (Spandau Ballet song)|True]]\" by [[Spandau Ballet]].<ref>{{cite news|title=How we made: Gary Kemp and Steve Norman on True|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2012/may/14/how-we-made-true-spandau-ballet|accessdate=13 May 2017|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nGrogan began presenting shows on [[Absolute Radio 80s]] from 11 September 2017, presenting Monday to Thursday 8-9pm and Sundays 7-9pm.<ref name=\"Absolute\" />\n\n==Writing==\nGrogan's first book was published in October 2008, a children's novel (aimed at age 7 and up) titled ''Tallulah and the Teenstars'', about a girl who forms a pop band.<ref name=book/>\n\n==Personal life==\nGrogan married band mate Stephen Lironi in Glasgow in 1994. The couple live in [[London Borough of Haringey|Haringey]], and in 2005 they [[adoption|adopted]] a daughter, Ellie.<ref name=\"Mirror Baby Girl\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs = \n<ref name=stv>{{cite web |title=Biographies: Clare Grogan |publisher=STV |date=20 March 2009 |url=http://programmes.stv.tv/scotland-at-the-movies/people/83611-clare-grogan/ |accessdate=6 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201072741/http://programmes.stv.tv/scotland-at-the-movies/people/83611-clare-grogan |archivedate=1 February 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Metro Ian Beale\">{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Clare Grogan: Kissing Ian Beale wasn't so bad, actually (interview)|work=Metro|date=10 April 2003|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/showbiz/interviews/966-clare-grogan|accessdate=5 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Mirror Baby Girl\">{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Clare Grogan: Love at first sight when I met my baby girl|work=The Mirror|date=29 September 2006|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/lifestyle/family/clare-grogan-love-at-first-sight-643699|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=stv2>[http://programmes.stv.tv/scotland-at-the-movies/interviews/83615-attack-on-gregorys-girl/ Scotland at the Movies: ''Attack on Gregory's Girl.''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006025809/http://programmes.stv.tv/scotland-at-the-movies/interviews/83615-attack-on-gregorys-girl/ |date=6 October 2011 }} Retrieved 23 August 2011.</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"John Shuttleworth\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b083m575|title=BBC Radio 4 - John Shuttleworth's Lounge Music, Series 2, Episode 2|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=sta>[http://special.lib.gla.ac.uk/sta/search/detaile.cfm?EID=14949 Scottish Theatre Archive] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103212456/http://special.lib.gla.ac.uk/sta/search/detaile.cfm?EID=14949 |date=3 November 2012 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=standard>{{cite news\n| title = Altered Images - Now Claire must change her name\n| work = [[Evening Standard]]\n| date = 21 August 1984\n| url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=y9lAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=waYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6044,3571634\n| accessdate = 24 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=book>{{cite news\n| title = Singer Clare Grogan launches children's book\n| work = [[Birmingham Mail]]\n| date = 23 October 2008\n| url = http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/local-news/singer-clare-grogan-launches-childrens-71395\n| accessdate = 24 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=herald>{{cite news\n| title = Alter Girl\n| work = [[The Herald (Glasgow)]]\n| date = 8 September 2007\n| url = http://www.heraldscotland.com/alter-girl-1.835488\n| accessdate = 24 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Absolute\">{{cite web|title=Clare Grogan to host nightly on Absolute 80s|url=https://radiotoday.co.uk/2017/09/clare-grogan-to-host-nightly-on-absolute-80s/|website=Radio Today|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{external media | width = 210px | align = right | headerimage= | video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iWHhcJAb75s Clare Grogan talking about adoption for BAAF at YouTube.]}}\n*{{IMDb name|id=00342931|name=Clare Grogan}}\n*[http://www.sukeplow.demon.co.uk/altered/grogan.htm Two interviews re early career]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110417024808/http://www.baaf.org.uk/about/president BAAF patrons]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Absolute Radio}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grogan, Clare}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Female new wave singers]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish film actresses]]\n[[Category:Scottish television actresses]]\n[[Category:Scottish female singers]]\n[[Category:Scottish new wave musicians]]\n[[Category:Scottish songwriters]]\n[[Category:People educated at Notre Dame High School, Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century women singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the actress and singer|the camogie player|Claire Grogan}}\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2009}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n<!--PLEASE NOTE:  the references in this article are in a list format, which means the data for the refs is in the References section, not in the body of the article.  If you add a new ref, please follow this format.  If you delete some text that includes a ref, please preview the whole page and check that you haven't created a ref error in the References section.\n-->\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name       = Clare Grogan\n| image      = Clare Grogan.jpg\n| caption    = Grogan performing with Altered Images\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1962|03|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| other_names =\n| genre       = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[rock music|rock]], [[New wave music|new wave]]\n| occupation = Singer, actress\n| background = solo_singer <!-- includes lead singers of bands -->\n| associated_acts = [[Altered Images]]\n}}\n'''Claire Patricia Grogan''' (born 17 March 1962), known professionally as '''Clare Grogan''' or sometimes as '''C. P. Grogan''', is a Scottish actress and singer. She is best known as the lead singer of the 1980s [[new wave music]] group [[Altered Images]] and for supporting roles in the 1981 film ''[[Gregory's Girl]]'' and the science fiction sitcom ''[[Red Dwarf]]'' as the first incarnation of [[Kristine Kochanski]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dave.uktv.co.uk/red-dwarf/red-dwarf-cast/article/clare-grogan-profile/|accessdate=9 February 2020|title=Clare Grogan}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Glasgow]], Grogan and her two sisters all attended the [[Notre Dame High School (Glasgow)|Notre Dame Convent School]].<ref name=stv/>\n\nAged 17 while dancing at the Glasgow College of Technology, a fight broke out nearby between several patrons. Grogan attempted to head away from the violence but was injured by thrown broken glass, causing a deep facial wound and prominent scar on the left side of her face. Grogan states that her parents still find it hard to read about the incident. She began filming ''Gregory's Girl'' just three months after the incident.<ref name=\"Metro Ian Beale\"/> In 1998, while she was working in Theatre at Watford, it was discovered part of the glass was still in the facial tissue and had to be surgically removed. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/uk/the-herald-1130/20111114/282106338437237|title=Centre Stage:Clare Gorgan on Success|website=www.pressreader.com|publisher=The Herald|date=2011-11-14}}</ref>\n\n==Acting career==\nOriginally a member of Scottish Youth Theatre, she was originally obliged to appear as 'C.P. Grogan' because there was already a member of [[Equity (trade union)|Equity]] named Claire Grogan (the other Claire Grogan went on to become a photographer). She would later drop the ''i'' from her first name.<ref name=standard/>\n\nWhile working as a [[waitress]] at the Spaghetti Factory [[restaurant]] in Glasgow, she was spotted by film director [[Bill Forsyth]].<ref name=herald/> This led to her breakthrough acting role in 1981's ''[[Gregory's Girl]]'' as Susan. Because of her facial wound there were objections from the producers, but Forsyth refused to recast the role and Grogan was filmed mostly in profile. When filmed in close up, makeup artists covered Grogan's scar with Derma wax.<ref name=stv2/>{{dead link|date=May 2014}}\n\nIn 1984, she played Charlotte in Forsyth's ''[[Comfort and Joy (1984 film)|Comfort and Joy]]''. In 1985, she was the receptionist in the [[BBC Television]] version of ''[[Blott on the Landscape]]''. She had a recurring role playing [[Red Dwarf characters#David Lister|Dave Lister]]'s would-be [[love-interest]], [[Kristine Kochanski]], in series 1, 2 and 6 of the TV show ''[[Red Dwarf]]''. However she was deemed too old for the role by Series 7 - despite being younger than most of her male counterparts - and replaced by [[Chlo\u00eb Annett]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/12803442.how-clare-survived-25-years-in-showbiz/|title=How Clare survived 25 years in showbiz|website=Evening Times}}</ref>. Grogan has also appeared in ''[[Father Ted]]'' (episode \"[[Rock-a-Hula Ted]]\") as a feminist rock singer and in ''[[EastEnders]]'' as [[Ian Beale]]'s love interest, [[Ros Thorne]] (1997\u20131998).\n\nGrogan played the part of Rita in a stage adaptation of ''[[Educating Rita]]'' at Dundee Repertory Theatre in 1987.<ref name=sta/>\n\nIn 1996 she played a fitness instructor on the [[Edinburgh Fringe]] in the play ''[[Lady Macbeth Firmed My Buttocks]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/fringe-round-up-lady-macbeth-firmed-my-buttocks-1309779.html|title=fringe round-up: Lady Macbeth Firmed My Buttocks|date=15 August 1996|website=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nShe had the role of Maggie in a 1998 comedy ''Jilting Joe'', played an Eye-Surgeon in a 2002 short film ''Bury It'', appeared in ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'' in 2003, and performed another [[Edinburgh Fringe]] play ''Forbidden'' in 2004, as Lily, married to a WW2 Nazi officer but falling in love with a young Jewish woman. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edinburghguide.com/news/theatre/8289-claregrogantopresentcriticsawardfortheatreinscotland|title=Clare Grogan to Present Critics' Award for Theatre in Scotland - Edinburgh Guide|website=www.edinburghguide.com}}</ref> \n\nIn 2006 Grogan portrayed Sandra Reeves, a control-freak office manager, in a film ''The Penalty King'' <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theargus.co.uk/news/5103049.altered-images-star-films-in-brighton/|title=Altered Images star films in Brighton|website=The Argus}}</ref> played Cathy in an episode of ''[[Sea of Souls]]'', and May, Danny's mother, in the Scottish sit-com ''[[Legit (2006 TV series)|Legit]]''. She appeared in the video for [[Peter Kay]] and [[Matt Lucas]]' charity single \"[[I'm Gonna Be (500 Miles)#Comic Relief|I'm Gonna Be (500 Miles)]]\", recorded for [[Comic Relief (charity)|Comic Relief]]'s Red Nose Day 2007, along with two TV films ''Wedding Belles'' and ''Forgiven''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0342931/|title=Clare Grogan|website=IMDb}}</ref>\n\nGrogan had a role in the 2011 TV series ''[[Skins (TV series)|Skins]]'' as Shelley, mother of [[Mini McGuinness]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/a302415/clare-grogan-explains-skins-role/|title=Clare Grogan explains 'Skins' role|first=Catriona|last=Wightman|date=7 February 2011|website=Digital Spy}}</ref> and played Jenny Ferris in the Scottish gangster film ''[[The Wee Man]]'' in 2013. \nS\nhe starred as Myriam in the 2017 film ''Delirium'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news-2-15012/interview-clare-grogan-1-4535598|title=Interview: Clare Grogan|website=www.scotsman.com}}</ref> filmed entirely at [[Royal Holloway, University of London]].\n\n==Music career==\nGrogan developed her singing career as the lead singer of [[Altered Images]], originally a five-piece band that included [[Johnny McElhone]] (later of the Scottish [[rock band]] [[Texas (band)|Texas]]), whom she met while studying for her [[Higher (Scottish)|Highers]]. It became a four-person band with the departure of two members and the addition of Stephen Lironi, who played both [[guitar]] and [[drum kit|drums]]. The band had a string of hits in the early 1980s, including \"[[Happy Birthday (Altered Images song)|Happy Birthday]]\", \"[[Don't Talk to Me About Love]]\", \"[[I Could Be Happy]]\" and \"See Those Eyes\". The group split up after the release of their third album, ''[[Bite (Altered Images album)|Bite]]'' (1983).\n\nIn 1984, Grogan made a cameo appearance in the music video to \"[[Young at Heart (Bananarama song)|Young at Heart]]\" by [[The Bluebells]].\n\nGrogan later attempted a [[solo (music)|solo]] career, but after her [[single (music)|single]] \"Love Bomb\" failed to gain chart success in 1987, her album ''Trash Mad'' was never released. Grogan formed Universal Love School in 1989 with Lironi, performing a series of gigs around the UK. However, it was short-lived and produced no hit singles. In 2000, she contributed vocals to the song \"Night Falls Like a Grand Piano\" on [[The 6ths]]' album ''[[Hyacinths and Thistles]]''. She recorded a version of \"Angels with Dirty Faces\" for the [[Frankie Miller]] tribute album. The track \"Her Hooped Dream\" appears on ''The Ultimate Celtic Album''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Ultimate-Celtic-Album-Various-artists/dp/B005FY0E5M|accessdate=9 February 2020|title=The Ultimate Celtic Album}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Grogan performed as 'Altered Images' on the [[Here and Now Tour]] which featured other well known artists from the 1980s. She performed on similar tours in 2005, 2008 and 2009. She appeared with [[Chesney Hawkes]], [[Toyah Willcox]] and [[Limahl]] as 'The 80s Supergroup' in the 2011 series of ''[[Let's Dance for Comic Relief]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/1NWMGqXS1Rwy5Svp726DqK1/contestants-the-final|accessdate=9 February 2020|title=Contestants - The Final}}</ref>\n\nGrogan sometimes covers for radio presenters on [[BBC 6 Music]], most often for [[Nemone]] and sometimes [[Liz Kershaw]].{{cn|date=December 2018}}\n\nGrogan appeared in Series 2, Episode 2 of [[John Shuttleworth (character)|John Shuttleworth's]] Lounge Music on [[BBC Radio 4]] on 27 November 2016.<ref name = \"John Shuttleworth\" />\n\nClare Grogan is the inspiration for the song \"[[True (Spandau Ballet song)|True]]\" by [[Spandau Ballet]].<ref>{{cite news|title=How we made: Gary Kemp and Steve Norman on True|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2012/may/14/how-we-made-true-spandau-ballet|accessdate=13 May 2017|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nGrogan began presenting shows on [[Absolute Radio 80s]] from 11 September 2017, presenting Monday to Thursday 8-9pm and Sundays 7-9pm.<ref name=\"Absolute\" />\n\n==Writing==\nGrogan's first book was published in October 2008, a children's novel (aimed at age 7 and up) titled ''Tallulah and the Teenstars'', about a girl who forms a pop band.<ref name=book/>\n\n==Personal life==\nGrogan married band mate Stephen Lironi in Glasgow in 1994. The couple live in [[London Borough of Haringey|Haringey]], and in 2005 they [[adoption|adopted]] a daughter, Ellie.<ref name=\"Mirror Baby Girl\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs = \n<ref name=stv>{{cite web |title=Biographies: Clare Grogan |publisher=STV |date=20 March 2009 |url=http://programmes.stv.tv/scotland-at-the-movies/people/83611-clare-grogan/ |accessdate=6 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201072741/http://programmes.stv.tv/scotland-at-the-movies/people/83611-clare-grogan |archivedate=1 February 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Metro Ian Beale\">{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Clare Grogan: Kissing Ian Beale wasn't so bad, actually (interview)|work=Metro|date=10 April 2003|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/showbiz/interviews/966-clare-grogan|accessdate=5 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Mirror Baby Girl\">{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Clare Grogan: Love at first sight when I met my baby girl|work=The Mirror|date=29 September 2006|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/lifestyle/family/clare-grogan-love-at-first-sight-643699|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=stv2>[http://programmes.stv.tv/scotland-at-the-movies/interviews/83615-attack-on-gregorys-girl/ Scotland at the Movies: ''Attack on Gregory's Girl.''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006025809/http:/